# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The site was previously occupied by a mansion known as Alder Hey which the local poor law guardians acquired for use as a children's home in 1910.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The mansion was converted for use as a military hospital in 1914.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] During the First World War, the United States Army established Camp Hospital 40 on the site, operated by Hospital Unit Q and, subsequently, Unit W.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] American sources commonly refer to Alder Hey as being within Liverpool's Knotty Ash area.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] During the Second World War, parts of the hospital were again used to treat injured military personnel.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The Liverpool Neonatal Surgical Unit opened at the hospital in 1953.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] This unit was the first neonatal intensive care unit in the United Kingdom.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The opening was largely due to the efforts of Isabella Forshall, a paediatric surgeon.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In 1990 when Myrtle Street Children's Hospital (founded in 1869 and previously known as Royal Liverpool Children's Hospital) closed, Alder Hey absorbed its A&E department.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The hospital authority was one of 57 such bodies which became an NHS hospital trust in 1991.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Ronald McDonald House, a home for the families of sick children, opened in 1993.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In 1999 an inquiry was instituted into the Alder Hey organs scandal and to investigate the hospital's practices in respect of removal and retention of human tissue.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The inquiry had far-reaching effects throughout the UK hospital system and provided the impetus for the Human Tissue Act 2004.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In August 2008 the Royal Liverpool Children's NHS Trust became an NHS foundation trust and changed its name to Alder Hey NHS Foundation Trust.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Between 2010 and 2014 the number of doctors employed at the trust increased from 269 to 344, while the number of managers increased from 70 to 86.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] At the end of March 2017, the trust was confirmed as one of four additional NHS Global Digital Exemplars, joining the twelve announced in September 2016.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Alder Hey had its centenary year in 2014, the last year in which it operated from the buildings on its original site.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] A new hospital was procured under Private Finance Initiative contract in neighbouring Springfield Park.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The works, which were carried out by Laing O'Rourke at a cost of £187 million, began on 26 March 2013 and the hospital opened in October 2015.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] It was Europe's first children's hospital built in a park.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The original Alder Hey buildings were mostly demolished and the land was reclaimed as new parkland for the surrounding community.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Features of the new hospital include access to play areas, natural light and striking views of the park are available wherever possible Children and young people were involved with the design of the new hospital.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] A drawing of a flower by teenage patient Eleanor Brogan impressed architects and inspired their final design.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The hospital is a centre of excellence for oncology and muscular dystrophy as well as spinal, heart and brain conditions.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Alder Hey has Europe's first 3T Intraoperative MRI scanner which is a pioneering technology for neurosurgery, providing surgeons with extremely high resolution images and reducing the need for repeat operations in 90% of cases.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] It currently employs about 2,400 staff and treats over 270,000 children from across the UK each year.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Alder Hey conducts paediatric research into children's medicines, infection, inflammation and oncology.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] It has research partners including the University of Liverpool and is a member of Liverpool Health Partners.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Alder Hey conducts more than 100 clinical research studies on an ongoing basis, ranging from observation to clinical trials.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The hospital is within the National Institute for Health and Care Research's Top 100 Performing Trust's for participation recruitment in 2013/14.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Alder Hey was a finalist in the Clinical Research Impact category of the 2013 HSJ Awards and in 2014 the innovation team received the Health Service Journal Award for improving health care with technology.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In 2016 the first phase of a bespoke research, education and innovation centre, Institute in the Park, opened next to Alder Hey in the Park.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In November 2015, the institute hosted a children's health Hackathon in conjunction with Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Alder Hey Children's Charity supports the work of the hospital.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In addition to NHS funding which covers the running costs of the hospital, Alder Hey relies on charitable support.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Funds are spent directly on initiatives in the hospital to benefit patients.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] It funds research initiatives, patient and family enhancements and state of the art medical equipment.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Known as the 'Imagine Appeal' until 2012, Alder Hey Children's Charity is based within the hospital.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] On 14 October 2013 the charity launched a public appeal to raise £30m to fund equipment, facilities and research at Alder Hey's new hospital, Alder Hey in the Park.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In October 2015 the charity announced over £20m had been raised.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In 2009 charitable support allowed Alder Hey to buy Europe's first 3T intraoperative MRI scanner.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In one charitably funded project, the sound recordist and musician Chris Watson was employed to devise an art project, using bird song recordings made by children to calm other young patients as they received injections and other treatments.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In 1978, the charity Art For Their Sake, a team of volunteer artists led by founder George Nicholas (now of Ormskirk, England), produced the world's longest mural in the corridors of Alder Hey Children's Hospital.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] A Guinness Record was set with a total of 17,963 square feet of murals, and awarded to the hospital in 1986.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Nicholas and his team continued to work on these murals for a period of 30 years, adding to as well as restoring and maintaining, for a total of over 34,000 square feet.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Alder Hey runs an Arts for Health programme, funded entirely through charitable sources including Alder Hey Children's Charity.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The programme aims to enhance the experience of being a patient and includes animation projects, music and dance therapy, creative writing, comedy workshops and storytelling.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] An international child health development programme led by Alder Hey clinicians focuses on humanitarian work in developing countries.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The programme includes provision of immediate medical support, knowledge sharing and involvement with international clinical trials.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The programme has undertaken work across Africa and Asia, including Pakistan, Malawi, Nepal and India.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] During the 1990s, Alder Hey was featured in the BBC television series *Children's Hospital*.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In 2011, chef Heston Blumenthal took to the challenge of changing the dinner menu of Alder Hey Children's Hospital on his televised show, *Heston's Mission Impossible*.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Since September 2012, Alder Hey has regularly featured on the CBBC television series *Operation Ouch!*.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In October 2013, the Care Quality Commission's Intelligent Monitoring system placed Alder Hey in category one, meaning it would be amongst the first hospitals to be inspected under a new style of inspection.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In May 2014, Alder Hey was inspected by the Care Quality Commission and was given the overall rating Requires Improvement.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In June 2015, Alder Hey was re-inspected by the Care Quality Commission and was given the overall rating Good, and was rated Outstanding in the Caring category.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Another inspection took place in 2018, the overall rating was unchanged.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Dame Josephine Williams was appointed Chair of the Trust Board in February 2019.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Louise Shepherd CBE was appointed Chief Executive of the trust in March 2008.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] On 26 January 2023, the Alder Hey Children's Hospital NHS Foundation Trust was granted the Honorary Freedom of the Metropolitan Borough of Sefton.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] In 2019, it was reported in an Ofcom report that the BBC spent £136m on news during the period April 2018 to March 2019.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] BBC News' domestic, global and online news divisions are housed within the largest live newsroom in Europe, in Broadcasting House in central London.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] Parliamentary coverage is produced and broadcast from studios in London.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] Through BBC English Regions, the BBC also has regional centres across England and national news centres in Northern Ireland, Scotland and Wales.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] All nations and English regions produce their own local news programmes and other current affairs and sport programmes.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] The BBC is a quasi-autonomous corporation authorised by royal charter, making it operationally independent of the government.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] As of 2024, the BBC reaches an average of 450 million people per week, with the BBC World Service accounting for 320 million people.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] The British Broadcasting Company broadcast its first radio bulletin from radio station 2LO on 14 November 1922.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] Wishing to avoid competition, newspaper publishers persuaded the government to ban the BBC from broadcasting news before 7 pm, and to force it to use wire service copy instead of reporting on its own.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] The BBC gradually gained the right to edit the copy and, in 1934, created its own news operation.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] However, it could not broadcast news before 6 p.m. until World War II.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] In addition to news, Gaumont British and Movietone cinema newsreels had been broadcast on the TV service since 1936, with the BBC producing its own equivalent *Television Newsreel* programme from January 1948.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] A weekly *Children's Newsreel* was inaugurated on 23 April 1950, to around 350,000 receivers.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] The network began simulcasting its radio news on television in 1946, with a still picture of Big Ben.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] Televised bulletins began on 5 July 1954, broadcast from leased studios within Alexandra Palace in London.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] The public's interest in television and live events was stimulated by Elizabeth II's coronation in 1953.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] It is estimated that up to 27 million people viewed the programme in the UK, overtaking radio's audience of 12 million for the first time.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] Those live pictures were fed from 21 cameras in central London to Alexandra Palace for transmission, and then on to other UK transmitters opened in time for the event.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] That year, there were around two million TV Licences held in the UK, rising to over three million the following year, and four and a half million by 1955.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] Television news, although physically separate from its radio counterpart, was still firmly under radio news' control in the 1950s.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] Correspondents provided reports for both outlets, and the first televised bulletin, shown on 5 July 1954 on the then BBC television service and presented by Richard Baker, involved his providing narration off-screen while stills were shown.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] This was then followed by the customary *Television Newsreel* with a recorded commentary by John Snagge (and on other occasions by Andrew Timothy).
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] On-screen newsreaders were introduced a year later in 1955 – Kenneth Kendall (the first to appear in vision), Robert Dougall, and Richard Baker—three weeks before ITN's launch on 21 September 1955.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] Mainstream television production had started to move out of Alexandra Palace in 1950 to larger premises – mainly at Lime Grove Studios in Shepherd's Bush, west London – taking Current Affairs (then known as Talks Department) with it.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] It was from here that the first *Panorama*, a new documentary programme, was transmitted on 11 November 1953, with Richard Dimbleby becoming anchor in 1955.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] In 1958, Hugh Carleton Greene became head of News and Current Affairs.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] On 1 January 1960, Greene became Director-General.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] Greene made changes that were aimed at making BBC reporting more similar to its competitor ITN, which had been highly rated by study groups held by Greene.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] A newsroom was created at Alexandra Palace, television reporters were recruited and given the opportunity to write and voice their own scripts, without having to cover stories for radio too.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] On 20 June 1960, Nan Winton, the first female BBC network newsreader, appeared in vision.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] 19 September 1960 saw the start of the radio news and current affairs programme *The Ten O'clock News*.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] BBC2 started transmission on 20 April 1964 and began broadcasting a new show, *Newsroom*.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] On Sunday 17 September 1967, *The World This Weekend*, a weekly news and current affairs programme, launched on what was then Home Service, but soon-to-be Radio 4.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] Preparations for colour began in the autumn of 1967 and on Thursday 7 March 1968 *Newsroom* on BBC2 moved to an early evening slot, becoming the first UK news programme to be transmitted in colour – from Studio A at Alexandra Palace.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] *News Review* and *Westminster* (the latter a weekly review of Parliamentary happenings) were "colourised" shortly after.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] However, much of the insert material was still in black and white, as initially only a part of the film coverage shot in and around London was on colour reversal film stock, and all regional and many international contributions were still in black and white.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] Colour facilities at Alexandra Palace were technically very limited for the next eighteen months, as it had only one RCA colour Quadruplex videotape machine and, eventually two Pye plumbicon colour telecines–although the news colour service started with just one.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] *Town and Around* was never to make the move to Television Centre – instead it became *London This Week* which aired on Mondays and Fridays only, from the new TVC studios.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] The BBC moved production out of Alexandra Palace in 1969.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] BBC Television News resumed operations the next day with a lunchtime bulletin on BBC1 – in black and white – from Television Centre, where it remained until March 2013.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] This move to a smaller studio with better technical facilities allowed *Newsroom* and *News Review* to replace back projection with colour-separation overlay.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] During the 1960s, satellite communication had become possible; however, it was some years before digital line-store conversion was able to undertake the process seamlessly.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] On 14 September 1970, the first *Nine O'Clock News* was broadcast on television.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] Robert Dougall presented the first week from studio N1 – described by *The Guardian* as "a sort of polystyrene padded cell"—the bulletin having been moved from the earlier time of 20.50 as a response to the ratings achieved by ITN's *News at Ten*, introduced three years earlier on the rival ITV.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] Richard Baker and Kenneth Kendall presented subsequent weeks, thus echoing those first television bulletins of the mid-1950s.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] Angela Rippon became the first female news presenter of the *Nine O'Clock News* in 1975.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] Her work outside the news was controversial at the time, appearing on *The Morecambe and Wise Christmas Show* in 1976 singing and dancing.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] The first edition of *John Craven's Newsround*, initially intended only as a short series and later renamed just *Newsround*, came from studio N3 on 4 April 1972.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] Afternoon television news bulletins during the mid to late 1970s were broadcast from the BBC newsroom itself, rather than one of the three news studios.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] The newsreader would present to camera while sitting on the edge of a desk; behind him staff would be seen working busily at their desks.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] This period corresponded with when the *Nine O'Clock News* got its next makeover, and would use a CSO background of the newsroom from that very same camera each weekday evening.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] Also in the mid-1970s, the late night news on BBC2 was briefly renamed *Newsnight*, but this was not to last, or be the same programme as we know today – that would be launched in 1980 – and it soon reverted to being just a news summary with the early evening BBC2 news expanded to become *Newsday*.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] News on radio was to change in the 1970s, and on Radio 4 in particular, brought about by the arrival of new editor Peter Woon from television news and the implementation of the *Broadcasting in the Seventies* report.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] These included the introduction of correspondents into news bulletins where previously only a newsreader would present, as well as the inclusion of content gathered in the preparation process.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] New programmes were also added to the daily schedule, *PM* and *The World Tonight* as part of the plan for the station to become a "wholly speech network".
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] *Newsbeat* launched as the news service on Radio 1 on 10 September 1973.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] On 23 September 1974, a teletext system which was launched to bring news content on television screens using text only was launched.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] Engineers originally began developing such a system to bring news to deaf viewers, but the system was expanded.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] The Ceefax service became much more diverse before it ceased on 23 October 2012: it not only had subtitling for all channels, it also gave information such as weather, flight times and film reviews.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] By the end of the decade, the practice of shooting on film for inserts in news broadcasts was declining, with the introduction of ENG technology into the UK.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] The equipment would gradually become less cumbersome – the BBC's first attempts had been using a Philips colour camera with backpack base station and separate portable Sony U-matic recorder in the latter half of the decade.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] In 1980, the Iranian Embassy Siege had been shot electronically by the BBC Television News Outside broadcasting team, and the work of reporter Kate Adie, broadcasting live from Prince's Gate, was nominated for BAFTA actuality coverage, but this time beaten by ITN for the 1980 award.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] The first BBC breakfast television programme, *Breakfast Time* also launched during the 1980s, on 17 January 1983 from Lime Grove Studio E and two weeks before its ITV rival TV-am.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] Frank Bough, Selina Scott, and Nick Ross helped to wake viewers with a relaxed style of presenting.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] The *Six O'Clock News* first aired on 3 September 1984, eventually becoming the most watched news programme in the UK (however, since 2006 it has been overtaken by the *BBC News at Ten*).
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] In October 1984, images of millions of people starving to death in the Ethiopian famine were shown in Michael Buerk's *Six O'Clock News* reports.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] The BBC News crew were the first to document the famine, with Buerk's report on 23 October describing it as "a biblical famine in the 20th century" and "the closest thing to hell on Earth".
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] The BBC News report shocked Britain, motivating its citizens to inundate relief agencies, such as Save the Children, with donations, and to bring global attention to the crisis in Ethiopia.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] The news report was also watched by Bob Geldof, who would organise the charity single "Do They Know It's Christmas?" to raise money for famine relief followed by the Live Aid concert in July 1985.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] Starting in 1981, the BBC gave a common theme to its main news bulletins with new electronic titles–a set of computer-animated "stripes" forming a circle on a red background with a "BBC News" typescript appearing below the circle graphics, and a theme tune consisting of brass and keyboards.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] The *Nine* used a similar (striped) number 9.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] The red background was replaced by a blue from 1985 until 1987.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] In 1987, John Birt resurrected the practice of correspondents working for both TV and radio with the introduction of bi-media journalism.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] During the 1990s, a wider range of services began to be offered by BBC News, with the split of BBC World Service Television to become BBC World (news and current affairs), and BBC Prime (light entertainment).
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] Content for a 24-hour news channel was thus required, followed in 1997 with the launch of domestic equivalent BBC News 24.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] Rather than set bulletins, ongoing reports and coverage was needed to keep both channels functioning and meant a greater emphasis in budgeting for both was necessary.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] In 1998, after 66 years at Broadcasting House, the **BBC Radio News** operation moved to BBC Television Centre.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] New technology, provided by Silicon Graphics, came into use in 1993 for a re-launch of the main BBC 1 bulletins, creating a virtual set which appeared to be much larger than it was physically.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] The relaunch also brought all bulletins into the same style of set with only small changes in colouring, titles, and music to differentiate each.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] A computer generated cut-glass sculpture of the BBC coat of arms was the centrepiece of the programme titles until the large scale corporate rebranding of news services in 1999.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] In November 1997, BBC News Online was launched, following individual webpages for major news events such as the 1996 Olympic Games, 1997 general election, and the death of Princess Diana.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] In 1999, the biggest relaunch occurred, with BBC One bulletins, BBC World, BBC News 24, and BBC News Online all adopting a common style.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] One of the most significant changes was the gradual adoption of the corporate image by the BBC regional news programmes, giving a common style across local, national and international BBC television news.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] This also included *Newyddion*, the main news programme of Welsh language channel S4C, produced by BBC News Wales.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] Following the relaunch of BBC News in 1999, regional headlines were included at the start of the BBC One news bulletins in 2000.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] The English regions did however lose five minutes at the end of their bulletins, due to a new headline round-up at 18:55.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] 2000 also saw the *Nine O'Clock News* moved to the later time of 22:00.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] This was in response to ITN who had just moved their popular *News at Ten* programme to 23:00.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] ITN briefly returned *News at Ten* but following poor ratings when head-to-head against the BBC's *Ten O'Clock News*, the ITN bulletin was moved to 22.30, where it remained until 14 January 2008.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] The retirement in 2009 of Peter Sissons and departure of Michael Buerk from the *Ten O'Clock News* led to changes in the BBC One bulletin presenting team on 20 January 2003.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] The *Six O'Clock News* became double headed with George Alagiah and Sophie Raworth after Huw Edwards and Fiona Bruce moved to present the *Ten*.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] A new set design featuring a projected fictional newsroom backdrop was introduced, followed on 16 February 2004 by new programme titles to match those of BBC News 24.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] BBC News 24 and BBC World introduced a new style of presentation in December 2003, that was slightly altered on 5 July 2004 to mark 50 years of BBC Television News.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] On 7 March 2005 director general Mark Thompson launched the "Creative Futures" project to restructure the organisation.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] The individual positions of editor of the *One* and *Six O'Clock News* were replaced by a new daytime position in November 2005.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] Kevin Bakhurst became the first Controller of BBC News 24, replacing the position of editor.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] Amanda Farnsworth became daytime editor while Craig Oliver was later named editor of the *Ten O'Clock News*.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] Bulletins received new titles and a new set design in May 2006, to allow for *Breakfast* to move into the main studio for the first time since 1997.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] The new set featured Barco videowall screens with a background of the London skyline used for main bulletins and originally an image of cirrus clouds against a blue sky for *Breakfast*.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] This was later replaced following viewer criticism.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] The studio bore similarities with the ITN-produced ITV News in 2004, though ITN uses a CSO virtual studio rather than the actual screens at BBC News.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] BBC News became part of a new BBC Journalism group in November 2006 as part of a restructuring of the BBC.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] The then-Director of BBC News, Helen Boaden reported to the then-Deputy Director-General and head of the journalism group, Mark Byford until he was made redundant in 2010.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] On 18 October 2007, ED Mark Thompson announced a six-year plan, "Delivering Creative Futures" (based on his project begun in March 2005), merging the television current affairs department into a new "News Programmes" division.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] Thompson's announcement, in response to a £2 billion shortfall in funding, would, he said, deliver "a smaller but fitter BBC" in the digital age, by cutting its payroll and, in 2013, selling Television Centre.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] The various separate newsrooms for television, radio and online operations were merged into a single multimedia newsroom.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] Programme making within the newsrooms was brought together to form a multimedia programme making department.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] BBC World Service director Peter Horrocks said that the changes would achieve efficiency at a time of cost-cutting at the BBC.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] In his blog, he wrote that by using the same resources across the various broadcast media meant fewer stories could be covered, or by following more stories, there would be fewer ways to broadcast them.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] A new graphics and video playout system was introduced for production of television bulletins in January 2007.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] This coincided with a new structure to BBC World News bulletins, editors favouring a section devoted to analysing the news stories reported on.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] The first new BBC News bulletin since the *Six O'Clock News* was announced in July 2007 following a successful trial in the Midlands.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] The summary, lasting 90 seconds, has been broadcast at 20:00 on weekdays since December 2007 and bears similarities with *60 Seconds* on BBC Three, but also includes headlines from the various BBC regions and a weather summary.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] As part of a long-term cost cutting programme, bulletins were renamed the *BBC News at One*, *Six* and *Ten* respectively in April 2008 while BBC News 24 was renamed BBC News and moved into the same studio as the bulletins at BBC Television Centre.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] BBC World was renamed *BBC World News* and regional news programmes were also updated with the new presentation style, designed by Lambie-Nairn.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] 2008 also saw tri-media introduced across TV, radio, and online.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] The studio moves also meant that Studio N9, previously used for BBC World, was closed, and operations moved to the previous studio of BBC News 24.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] Studio N9 was later refitted to match the new branding, and was used for the BBC's UK local elections and European elections coverage in early June 2009.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] A strategy review of the BBC in March 2010, confirmed that having "the best journalism in the world" would form one of five key editorial policies, as part of changes subject to public consultation and BBC Trust approval.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] After a period of suspension in late 2012, Helen Boaden ceased to be the Director of BBC News.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] On 16 April 2013, incoming BBC Director-General Tony Hall named James Harding, a former editor of *The Times* of London newspaper as Director of News and Current Affairs.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] From August 2012 to March 2013, all news operations moved from Television Centre to new facilities in the refurbished and extended Broadcasting House, in Portland Place.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] The move began in October 2012, and also included the BBC World Service, which moved from Bush House following the expiry of the BBC's lease.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] This new extension to the north and east, referred to as "New Broadcasting House", includes several new state-of-the-art radio and television studios centred around an 11-storey atrium.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] The move began with the domestic programme *The Andrew Marr Show* on 2 September 2012, and concluded with the move of the BBC News channel and domestic news bulletins on 18 March 2013.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] The newsroom houses all domestic bulletins and programmes on both television and radio, as well as the BBC World Service international radio networks and the BBC World News international television channel.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] BBC News and CBS News established an editorial and newsgathering partnership in 2017, replacing an earlier long-standing partnership between BBC News and ABC News.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] In an October 2018 Simmons Research survey of 38 news organisations, BBC News was ranked the fourth most trusted news organisation by Americans, behind CBS News, ABC News and *The Wall Street Journal*.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] In January 2020 the BBC announced a BBC News savings target of £80 million per year by 2022, involving about 450 staff reductions from the current 6,000.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] BBC director of news and current affairs Fran Unsworth said there would be further moves toward digital broadcasting, in part to attract back a youth audience, and more pooling of reporters to stop separate teams covering the same news.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] A further 70 staff reductions were announced in July 2020.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] BBC Three began airing the news programme *The Catch Up* in February 2022.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] It is presented by Levi Jouavel, Kirsty Grant, and Callum Tulley and aims to get the channel's target audience (16 to 34-year olds) to make sense of the world around them while also highlighting optimistic stories.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] Compared to its predecessor *60 Seconds*, *The Catch Up* is three times longer, running for about three minutes and not airing during weekends.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] According to its annual report as of December 2021, India has the largest number of people using BBC services in the world.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] In May 2025, following the earthquake that hit Myanmar and Thailand, a television news bulletin (BBC News Myanmar) from the Burmese service using a vacated Voice of America satellite frequency began its broadcasts.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] Government officials including Cyprus president Nikos Christodoulides and European lawmakers began responding to the investigation's findings in less than 24 hours, calling for reforms and launching probes.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] BBC News is responsible for the news programmes and documentary content on the BBC's general television channels, as well as the news coverage on the BBC News Channel in the UK, and 22 hours of programming for the corporation's international BBC World News channel.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] Coverage for BBC Parliament is carried out on behalf of the BBC at Millbank Studios, though BBC News provides editorial and journalistic content.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] BBC News content is also output onto the BBC's digital interactive television services under the BBC Red Button brand, and until 2012, on the Ceefax teletext system.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] The music on all BBC television news programmes was introduced in 1999 and composed by David Lowe.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] It was part of the re-branding which commenced in 1999 and features 'BBC Pips'.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] The general theme was used on bulletins on BBC One, News 24, BBC World and local news programmes in the BBC's Nations and Regions.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] Lowe was also responsible for the music on Radio One's *Newsbeat*.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] The theme has had several changes since 1999, the latest in March 2013.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] The BBC Verify service was launched in 2023 to fact-check news stories, followed by BBC Verify Live in 2025.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] BBC Radio News produces bulletins for the BBC's national radio stations and provides content for local BBC radio stations via the General News Service (GNS), a BBC-internal news distribution service.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] BBC News does not produce the BBC's regional news bulletins, which are produced individually by the BBC nations and regions themselves.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] The BBC World Service broadcasts to some 150 million people in English as well as 27 languages across the globe.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] BBC Radio News is a patron of the Radio Academy.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] BBC News Online is the BBC's news website.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] Launched in November 1997, it is one of the most popular news websites, with 1.2 billion website visits in April 2021, as well as being used by 60% of the UK's internet users for news.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] The website contains international news coverage as well as entertainment, sport, science, and political news.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] Mobile apps for Android, iOS and Windows Phone systems have been provided since 2010.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] Many television and radio programmes are also available to view on the BBC iPlayer and BBC Sounds services.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] The BBC News channel is also available to view 24 hours a day, while video and radio clips are also available within online news articles.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] In October 2019, BBC News Online launched a mirror on the dark web anonymity network Tor in an effort to circumvent censorship.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] The BBC is required by its charter to be free from both political and commercial influence and answers only to its viewers and listeners.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] This political objectivity is sometimes questioned.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] For instance, *The Daily Telegraph* (3 August 2005) carried a letter from the KGB defector Oleg Gordievsky, referring to it as "The Red Service".
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] Books have been written on the subject, including anti-BBC works like *Truth Betrayed* by W J West and *The Truth Twisters* by Richard Deacon.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] The BBC has been accused of bias by Conservative MPs.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] The BBC's Editorial Guidelines on Politics and Public Policy state that while "the voices and opinions of opposition parties must be routinely aired and challenged", "the government of the day will often be the primary source of news".
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] The BBC is regularly accused by the government of the day of bias in favour of the opposition and, by the opposition, of bias in favour of the government.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] Similarly, during times of war, the BBC is often accused by the UK government, or by strong supporters of British military campaigns, of being overly sympathetic to the view of the enemy.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] An edition of *Newsnight* at the start of the Falklands War in 1982 was described as "almost treasonable" by John Page, MP, who objected to Peter Snow saying "if we believe the British".
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] During the first Gulf War, critics of the BBC took to using the satirical name "Baghdad Broadcasting Corporation".
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] Conversely, some of those who style themselves anti-establishment in the United Kingdom or who oppose foreign wars have accused the BBC of pro-establishment bias or of refusing to give an outlet to "anti-war" voices.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] Following the 2003 invasion of Iraq, a study by the Cardiff University School of Journalism of the reporting of the war found that nine out of 10 references to weapons of mass destruction during the war assumed that Iraq possessed them, and only one in 10 questioned this assumption.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] It also found that, out of the main British broadcasters covering the war, the BBC was the most likely to use the British government and military as its source.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] It was also the least likely to use independent sources, like the Red Cross, who were more critical of the war.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] When it came to reporting Iraqi casualties, the study found fewer reports on the BBC than on the other three main channels.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] The report's author, Justin Lewis, wrote "Far from revealing an anti-war BBC, our findings tend to give credence to those who criticised the BBC for being too sympathetic to the government in its war coverage.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] Prominent BBC appointments are constantly assessed by the British media and political establishment for signs of political bias.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] The appointment of Greg Dyke as Director-General was highlighted by press sources because Dyke was a Labour Party member and former activist, as well as a friend of Tony Blair.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] Mark Thompson, former Director-General of the BBC, admitted the organisation has been biased "towards the left" in the past.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] He said, "In the BBC I joined 30 years ago, there was, in much of current affairs, in terms of people's personal politics, which were quite vocal, a massive bias to the left".
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] He then added, "The organization did struggle then with impartiality.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] Now it is a completely different generation.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] Following the EU referendum in 2016, some critics suggested that the BBC was biased in favour of leaving the EU.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] For instance, in 2018, the BBC received complaints from people who took issue that the BBC was not sufficiently covering anti-Brexit marches while giving smaller-scale events hosted by former UKIP leader Nigel Farage more airtime.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] On the other hand, a poll released by YouGov showed that 45% of people who voted to leave the EU thought that the BBC was 'actively anti-Brexit' compared to 13% of the same kinds of voters who think the BBC is pro-Brexit.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] In 2008, the BBC Hindi was criticised by some Indian outlets for referring to the terrorists who carried out the 2008 Mumbai attacks as "gunmen".
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] The response to this added to prior criticism from some Indian commentators suggesting that the BBC may have an Indophobic bias.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] In March 2015, the BBC was criticised for a BBC *Storyville* documentary interviewing one of the rapists in India.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] In spite of a ban ordered by the Indian High court, the BBC still aired the documentary "India's Daughter" outside India.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] BBC News was at the centre of a political controversy following the 2003 invasion of Iraq.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] The government denounced the reports and accused the corporation of poor journalism.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] In subsequent weeks the corporation stood by the report, saying that it had a reliable source.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] Following intense media speculation, David Kelly was named in the press as the source for Gilligan's story on 9 July 2003.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] Kelly was found dead, by suicide, in a field close to his home early on 18 July.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] An inquiry led by Lord Hutton was announced by the British government the following day to investigate the circumstances leading to Kelly's death, concluding that "Dr.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] In his report on 28 January 2004, Lord Hutton concluded that Gilligan's original accusation was "unfounded" and the BBC's editorial and management processes were "defective".
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] In particular, it specifically criticised the chain of management that caused the BBC to defend its story.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] The BBC Director of News, Richard Sambrook, the report said, had accepted Gilligan's word that his story was accurate in spite of his notes being incomplete.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] Davies had then told the BBC Board of Governors that he was happy with the story and told the Prime Minister that a satisfactory internal inquiry had taken place.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] The Board of Governors, under the chairman's, Gavyn Davies, guidance, accepted that further investigation of the Government's complaints were unnecessary.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] Because of the criticism in the Hutton report, Davies resigned on the day of publication.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] BBC News faced an important test, reporting on itself with the publication of the report, but by common consent (of the Board of Governors) managed this "independently, impartially and honestly".
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] Davies' resignation was followed by the resignation of Director General, Greg Dyke, the following day, and the resignation of Gilligan on 30 January.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] While undoubtedly a traumatic experience for the corporation, an ICM poll in April 2003 indicated that it had sustained its position as the best and most trusted provider of news.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] The BBC has faced accusations of holding both anti-Israel and anti-Palestine bias.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] However two large independent studies, one conducted by Loughborough University and the other by Glasgow University's Media Group concluded that Israeli perspectives are given greater coverage.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] Critics of the BBC argue that the Balen Report proves systematic bias against Israel in headline news programming.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] The *Daily Mail* and *The Daily Telegraph* criticised the BBC for spending hundreds of thousands of British tax payers' pounds from preventing the report being released to the public.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] An independent panel appointed by the BBC Trust was set up in 2006 to review the impartiality of the BBC's coverage of the Israeli–Palestinian conflict.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] In some ways the picture is incomplete and, in that sense, misleading." It notes that, "the failure to convey adequately the disparity in the Israeli and Palestinian experience, [reflects] the fact that one side is in control and the other lives under occupation".
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] Writing in the *Financial Times*, Philip Stephens, one of the panellists, later accused the BBC's director-general, Mark Thompson, of misrepresenting the panel's conclusions.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] He further opined "My sense is that BBC news reporting has also lost a once iron-clad commitment to objectivity and a necessary respect for the democratic process.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] Mark Thompson published a rebuttal in the FT the next day.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] Walker argues that the independent inquiry was flawed for two reasons.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] Firstly, because the time period over which it was conducted (August 2005 to January 2006) surrounded the Israeli withdrawal from Gaza and Ariel Sharon's stroke, which produced more positive coverage than usual.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] Furthermore, he wrote, the inquiry only looked at the BBC's domestic coverage, and excluded output on the BBC World Service and BBC World.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] Tom Gross, writing for the *National Review*, criticised the BBC's coverage of Hamas suicide bombers, and its invitations of Jenny Tonge and Tom Paulin as guest commentators, claiming that Paulin had "compared Jewish settlers to Nazis".
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] Paulin had previously stated that Israeli settlers should be "shot dead", and said he could "understand how suicide bombers feel".
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] The BBC also faced criticism for not airing a Disasters Emergency Committee aid appeal for Palestinians who suffered in Gaza during 22-day war there between late 2008 and early 2009.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] Most other major UK broadcasters did air this appeal, but rival Sky News did not.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] British journalist Julie Burchill has accused BBC of creating a "climate of fear" for British Jews over its "excessive coverage" of Israel compared to other nations.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] In light of the Gaza war, the BBC suspended seven Arab journalists over allegations of expressing support for Hamas via social media.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] BBC and ABC share video segments and reporters as needed in producing their newscasts. with the BBC showing *ABC World News Tonight with David Muir* in the UK.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] However, in July 2017, the BBC announced a new partnership with CBS News allows both organisations to share video, editorial content, and additional newsgathering resources in New York, London, Washington and around the world.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] BBC News subscribes to wire services from leading international agencies including PA Media (formerly Press Association), Reuters, and Agence France-Presse.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] In April 2017, the BBC dropped Associated Press in favour of an enhanced service from AFP.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] BBC News reporters and broadcasts are now and have in the past been banned in several countries primarily for reporting which has been unfavourable to the ruling government.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] For example, correspondents were banned by the former apartheid regime of South Africa.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] The BBC was banned in Zimbabwe under Mugabe for eight years as a terrorist organisation until being allowed to operate again over a year after the 2008 elections.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] The BBC was banned in Burma (officially Myanmar) after their coverage and commentary on anti-government protests there in September 2007.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] The ban was lifted four years later in September 2011.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] Other cases have included Uzbekistan, China, and Pakistan.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] BBC Persian, the BBC's Persian language news site, was blocked from the Iranian internet in 2006.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] The BBC News website was made available in China again in March 2008, but as of October 2014, was blocked again.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] In June 2015, the Rwandan government placed an indefinite ban on BBC broadcasts following the airing of a controversial documentary regarding the 1994 Rwandan genocide, *Rwanda's Untold Story*, broadcast on BBC2 on 1 October 2014.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] The UK's Foreign Office recognised "the hurt caused in Rwanda by some parts of the documentary".
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] In February 2017, reporters from the BBC (as well as the *Daily Mail*, *The New York Times*, Politico, CNN, and others) were denied access to a United States White House briefing.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] In 2017, BBC India was banned for a period of five years from covering all national parks and sanctuaries in India.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bbc-news] Following the withdrawal of CGTN's UK broadcaster licence on 4 February 2021 by Ofcom, China banned BBC News from airing in China.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/beatson-west-of-scotland-cancer-centre] The **Beatson West of Scotland Cancer Centre** (BWSCC; formerly called the **Beatson Oncology Centre**) is a specialised cancer care centre in Glasgow, Scotland.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/beatson-west-of-scotland-cancer-centre] Until recently it had facilities in Gartnavel General Hospital, the Western Infirmary and Glasgow Royal Infirmary.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/beatson-west-of-scotland-cancer-centre] As part of the NHS Greater Glasgow and Clyde Acute Services Review, the centre is being centralised within new facilities at the Gartnavel General Hospital site.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/beatson-west-of-scotland-cancer-centre] The hospital has its origins in the Glasgow Cancer and Skin Institution which was founded in 1886 and later renamed after its first director of cancer services, Sir George Beatson.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/beatson-west-of-scotland-cancer-centre] The BWSCC was supported by charities Friends of the Beatson and The Beatson Oncology Centre Fund.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/beatson-west-of-scotland-cancer-centre] In 2014 through a restructuring, and in partnership with NHS Greater Glasgow and Clyde, the resources of both charities dedicated to supporting the Beatson West of Scotland Cancer Centre have combined to form a unitary charity to support and serve the Beatson.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/beatson-west-of-scotland-cancer-centre] The charity is named Beatson Cancer Charity.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/birmingham-children-s-hospital] The hospital was founded by Thomas Pretious Heslop as the *Birmingham and Midland Free Hospital for Sick Children* at 138–9 Steelhouse Lane in 1862.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/birmingham-children-s-hospital] It moved to a new site on Ladywood Middleway in 1917.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/birmingham-children-s-hospital] In March 1986, a charity concert was held called "Heart Beat 86" at the nearby National Exhibition Centre, featuring George Harrison, which raised money for the hospital.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/birmingham-children-s-hospital] In October 1998 the hospital returned to Steelhouse Lane, to the buildings previously used by the Birmingham General Hospital, as the Diana, Princess of Wales Children's Hospital – in honour of Diana, Princess of Wales, who had died the year before.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/birmingham-children-s-hospital] The opening ceremony was carried out by the Queen.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/birmingham-children-s-hospital] In 2007, a new extension designed by RPS Group was opened.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/birmingham-children-s-hospital] The extension created a burns unit, one of three such centres of excellence in the country.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/birmingham-children-s-hospital] As well as this, it established an outpatients department, a neonatal ward, a burns operating theatre, as well as additional classrooms for the Education Centre, allowing children to continue their education whilst undergoing medium to long-term care in the hospital.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/birmingham-children-s-hospital] The trust led a consortium of organisations called **Forward Thinking Birmingham** commissioned to provide mental health services for young people in the city up to the age of 25 from April 2016.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/birmingham-children-s-hospital] Services for adults were previously provided by Birmingham and Solihull Mental Health NHS Foundation Trust.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/birmingham-children-s-hospital] In 1970, surgeons completed the first separation of conjoined twins at the hospital.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/birmingham-children-s-hospital] The hospital was managed by the Birmingham Children's Hospital NHS Trust until 2017 when it merged with the Women's Hospital NHS Foundation Trust to create the Birmingham Women's and Children's NHS Foundation Trust.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/birmingham-children-s-hospital] The trust was named by the *Health Service Journal* as one of the top hundred NHS trusts to work for in 2015.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/birmingham-children-s-hospital] At that time it had 3236 full-time equivalent staff and a sickness absence rate of 3.39%.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/birmingham-children-s-hospital] 89% of staff recommend it as a place for treatment and 74% recommended it as a place to work.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/birmingham-children-s-hospital] The Trust's Professor Anita Macdonald, Consultant Paediatric Dietitian was awarded an OBE for services to Dietetics in the Queen's Birthday Honours 2015.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/birmingham-children-s-hospital] In 2016, it became the first children's hospital to be rated Outstanding by the Care Quality Commission.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] The hospital has its origins in the **Hospital for Sick Children** on St Michael's Hill founded in 1866.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] The initial building was a large converted dwelling house on Royal Fort Road, south of the Royal Fort gatehouse, with accommodation for 40 patients.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] One of the hospital's first salaried doctors was the pioneering female surgeon, Eliza Walker, appointed as House Surgeon in 1873.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] A much expanded hospital was built nearby to the designs of Robert Carwen in the Tudor gothic revival style in 1885.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] Only the entrance building fronting on to St Michael's Hill now survives.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] The hospital was later renamed as the **Bristol Royal Hospital for Sick Children**.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] The new Children's Hospital opened on 22 April 2001, replacing the old children's hospital on St Michael's Hill, at a cost £30 million.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] One of the main aims of the design, in addition to providing the most up-to-date facilities possible, was to overcome many of the difficulties that face patients, families and staff.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] In February 2014, it was agreed an inquiry would be held into the Bristol heart scandal, following heart surgery deaths at the hospital.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] The inquiry published a report in June 2016, saying that “parents had been let down”.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] An extension was built to accommodate services moved from Frenchay Hospital in 2014, including neuroscience, scoliosis surgery, burns and plastic surgery, bringing all inpatient children's services in Bristol to one location.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] In 2015, a neuro-rehabilitation unit was built to support the moved services.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] In May 2014, a new helipad on the roof of the neighbouring Bristol Royal Infirmary became fully operational and will receive air ambulances from Bristol and the surrounding area, which will speed up transfer times for patients who are air lifted to the hospital.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] The HELP Appeal supported the construction of the helipad with a grant of £500,000.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] Wallace & Gromit's Grand Appeal is the only charity that fundraises exclusively for the hospital and the neonatal intensive care unit at St Michael's Hospital, to provide facilities and comforts for patients and their families.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] The Grand Appeal raised £12M towards the new building for the child-friendly hospital, which opened in April 2001.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] Sculptures were decorated by a range of artists and celebrities, including Joanna Lumley, Sir Peter Blake, Cath Kidston and Jools Holland.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] At the end of the art trail, each sculpture was auctioned to raise funds for Bristol Children's Hospital.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] The Grand Appeal has pledged to raise £3.5M for equipment for Bristol Children's Hospital, including a state of the art CT Scanner, an intraoperative MRI scanner, family facilities and child-friendly artwork to help save the lives of sick children at the hospital.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] All funds raised by Gromit Unleashed will contribute towards this.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] Bristol & Weston Hospitals Charity (BWHC) raises around £2M for all ten hospitals in the trust.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] It provides equipment, ward refurbishments and additional extras.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] It was formerly known as Above & Beyond and has existed since 1974.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] In 2013, the charity's Golden Gift Appeal raised £6M.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] In 1997, arts consultant, Lesley Greene, was commissioned to develop an arts strategy for the new hospital.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] This project was committed to integrated designs, a commitment to consultation and the family.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] Her active research programme led to the appointment of lead artist, Ray Smith, Eva Elsner, and Annie Lovejoy who contributed to the planning of the commissions programme.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] Artworks were commissioned from more than twenty artists, many of which were site specific.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] These commissions were funded by the hospital's own fundraising arm, The Wallace and Gromit Grand Appeal.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] Records of the Bristol Royal Hospital for Children are held at Bristol Archives (Ref.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] 37424) (online catalogue) and School of Nursing records (Ref.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/children-s-acute-transport-service] The **Children's Acute Transport Service** (CATS) is a publicly funded specialised regional intensive care transport service for critically ill children.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/children-s-acute-transport-service] CATS is the busiest Paediatric Intensive Care Transport Service in the UK and covers the 50 District General Hospitals in the North Thames and East Anglia regions of England.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/children-s-acute-transport-service] CATS is part of the Great Ormond Street Hospital for Children NHS Foundation Trust.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/children-s-acute-transport-service] Only a proportion of hospitals have a Paediatric Intensive Care Unit PICU.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/children-s-acute-transport-service] Therefore, most critically ill children initially present to hospitals without a PICU.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/children-s-acute-transport-service] Paediatric Intensive Care Transport Services are designed to provide the safe and rapid transfer of these children to a regional PICU.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/children-s-acute-transport-service] CATS was created in 2001 as a collaborative service for the North Thames Regional PICU's: The Royal Brompton Hospital, St Mary's Hospital, London and Great Ormond Street Hospital for Children.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/children-s-acute-transport-service] CATS receives ~2200 referral calls and performs ~1200 critical care retrievals each year.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/children-s-acute-transport-service] Over 75% of these children are too unwell to breathe for themselves and require anaesthesia and a ventilator.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/children-s-acute-transport-service] A third need inotropic (inotrope) support, and about 5% require inhaled nitric oxide during transport.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/children-s-acute-transport-service] Telephone advice, liaison with sub-specialist medical services and outreach education are also important parts of the service's activity.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/children-s-acute-transport-service] Service Level Agreements (SLA) exist with Great Ormond Street Hospital and the Freeman Hospital in Newcastle for ECMO (extracorporeal membrane oxygenation) retrievals.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/children-s-acute-transport-service] CATS also provide a paediatric intensive care transport service with Great Ormond Street Hospital for retrieval of children with Vein of Galen malformations requiring radiological ablation.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/children-s-acute-transport-service] 5-10% of retrievals are performed by air ambulance.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/children-s-acute-transport-service] This is via both helicopter and fixed-wing aircraft.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/children-s-acute-transport-service] For many of these urgent long distance transfers, the team works with the aircraft and the crews of HM Coastguard helicopters.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/children-s-acute-transport-service] CATS have moved many paediatric patients internationally.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/children-s-acute-transport-service] CATS has received accreditation from the Commission on Accreditation of Medical Transport Systems (CAMTS).
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/children-s-acute-transport-service] This independent, non-profit agency audits medical transport services against industry-established criteria.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/children-s-acute-transport-service] CATS accreditation is for fixed-wing and rotary wing air medical transport services as well as ground inter-facility critical care services.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/children-s-acute-transport-service] Department of Health, Health and Social Care Award, National Winners 2005.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/children-s-acute-transport-service] NHS intensive care consultants are responsible for service delivery, supervision of junior medical staff, provision of outreach education and service development.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/children-s-acute-transport-service] All full-time CATS consultant intensivists, cover sessions in PICU/anaesthesia to maintain competencies in their base speciality.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/children-s-acute-transport-service] A team of full-time CATS nurses is responsible for service delivery, co-ordination of the outreach education program, and in-house training.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/children-s-acute-transport-service] In addition, over 50 nurses rotate from each of the 3 PICUs to cover the rota.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/children-s-acute-transport-service] A team of administrators provide 24-hour cover for the Referral Hotline and co-ordinate incoming referrals, teleconferencing and communication with clinical team members.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/children-s-acute-transport-service] Road ambulance retrievals are provided by St John Ambulance using bespoke CATS designed intensive care ambulances.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/children-s-acute-transport-service] CATS is the subject of an eight-part (8 x 30 minute) series called Children's Emergency, produced by September Films for BBC One.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/children-s-acute-transport-service] It aired between 4 May and 23 June 2010.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/children-s-hospice-south-west] CHSW was founded by Jill and Eddie Farwell in 1991, after spending many years travelling to Helen & Douglas House in Oxford with their own two life-limited children.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/children-s-hospice-south-west] Following a feasibility study, they raised funds and Little Bridge House at Fremington near Barnstaple in North Devon opened in 1995, and instantly provided support for up to 200 families in the South West with life limited children.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/children-s-hospice-south-west] The second hospice, Charlton Farm at Wraxall, North Somerset near Bristol, opened its doors to the first families in April 2007.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/children-s-hospice-south-west] The third hospice, Little Harbour, opened at Porthpean, St Austell, Cornwall in 2011.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/children-s-hospice-south-west] It offers a more local service to families from Cornwall and Plymouth.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/children-s-hospice-south-west] Children's Hospice South West's £5 million Precious Lives Appeal was set up to fund the building of this third hospice.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/children-s-hospice-south-west] In the year ending March 2020, CHSW's income was £15.8 million, which included £2.6M of government contracts and grants.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/children-s-hospice-south-west] It spent £5.8M on raising funds and £9.3M on running the hospices.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow] The **Royal Hospital for Children** is a 256-bed hospital specialising in paediatric healthcare for children and young people up to the age of 16.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow] The hospital is part of the Queen Elizabeth University Hospital and is built on the site of the former Southern General Hospital, in Govan and opened in June 2015.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow] The hospital replaced the Royal Hospital for Sick Children in Yorkhill.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow] It is managed by NHS Greater Glasgow and Clyde.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow] The Royal Hospital for Children, like the adjacent Queen Elizabeth University Hospital, was designed by Nightingale Associates, with construction carried out by Brookfield Multiplex, who previously built Wembley Stadium.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow] The new hospital was built on the site of the old Southern General Hospital.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow] In January 2010, NHS Greater Glasgow and Clyde closed the Queen Mother's Maternity Hospital at Yorkhill, with maternity services relocating to the Southern General Hospital.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow] Originally to be called Royal Hospital for Sick Children, it was named Royal Hospital for Children.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow] It was originally hoped the new hospital would be ready by 2014, but medical services did not start to be transferred until 10 June 2015.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow] The new children's hospital is a mix of four-bedded and single-bedded accommodation.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow] The design included a part covered roof garden where it was intended that young patients would be able to enjoy a range of activities in the fresh air.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow] In 2016 the roof garden play area was closed amid health and safety concerns.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow] The hospital has a 47-seat cinema, which was built in partnership with MediCinema costing around £250,000 to install.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow] In addition to the 47 seats the facility serves patients in wheelchairs and beds.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow] The Royal Hospital for Children, while retaining a somewhat separate identity from the Queen Elizabeth University Hospital, is adjoined and integrated with the adult hospital.
[src:royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow/royal-hospital-for-children-glasgow] With 256 beds and 5 floors, it replaced the Royal Hospital for Sick Children located in Yorkhill, Glasgow.
